{"source_key":"sha256-e5687aa6fc4c11d845e8d63e8ca8f175","record_index":183,"record_hash":"sha256:ed9fe66f5833de0c164d4c2e59b9de39f36ac28bd6d66618d38b5fb2fd8baeaa","timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:32:11.505Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Short version: this is not “agent memory.” It’s Git-native provenance: capture agent sessions, attach them to branches/PRs through `git-meta`, publish only selected metadata, then render a reviewer-safe PR trail.\\n\\n**Component View**\\n\\n| Component | What it’s for | How it stores/surfaces data | Key limits |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| `git-meta` | Generic metadata layer for Git objects/projects, intended as a better notes-like system for prompts, provenance, review, tests, etc. See [README.md]([REDACTED:path]) and [spec]([REDACTED:path]). | Local SQLite at `.git/git-meta.sqlite`; exchange via Git refs/trees, especially `refs/meta/*`. API is `Session -> Target -> MetaValue`; CLI has set/get/list/sync/materialize/push/pull. See [session.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [schema.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [cli.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | It’s infrastructure, not UX. Higher-level tools must decide what to capture, redact, publish, and display. Docs explicitly leave a lot of integration work out of scope. |\\n| `but-agentlog` | GitButler-specific capture and interpretation of coding-agent sessions. It turns Codex/Claude transcript JSONL plus GitButler workspace context into structured git metadata. See [Cargo.toml]([REDACTED:path]), [lib.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | Stores project-target keys like `gitbutler:agent-session:<id>` and `local:gitbutler:agent-session:<id>` through `git-meta`; indexes by branch/review/change/session. Write path is in [write.rs]([REDACTED:path]). CLI surface is `hook`, `show`, `skim`, `publish`, hidden `sync` in [cli.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | Target association is partly heuristic. Supports Codex/Claud\n[TRUNCATED]\nut-agentlog/src/projection.rs:1), [projection.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Reviewer UI states for ready, weak matches, missing metadata, unsupported fork, GitHub unavailable, etc. See [trail_contract.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Optional lazy summary/classification/signals/chat overlays in Agent Trail, off the critical path. See [http.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n**Limitations / Unknowns**\\n\\n- Association quality depends on captured GitButler environment and index hits; weak branch-only matches are explicitly modeled, not hidden.\\n- Redaction catches secrets, paths, UUIDs, entropy-looking tokens, and sensitive assignment names, but it is not a magic DLP guarantee. See [redaction.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Agent Trail docs warn it does not verify claims against the PR diff; the trail is context, not proof. See [agent-trail.md]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- `agent-trail` currently pins `but-agentlog`/`git-meta-lib` by Git revision, not local path deps, so sibling repo state may differ from the exact built dependency. See [Cargo.toml]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Private support exists in code, but docs still describe public-only v1. Treat that as an unresolved product/deployment boundary.\\n\\n**Why This Is Different From Generic Memory Tools**\\n\\nGeneric memory tools remember “what the agent/user said.” This stack preserves reviewable, Git-addressed evidence: what session touched which branch/review/change, how it relates to a PR, what got published, and what a reviewer is allowed to see.\\n\\nThe big difference is lifecycle and trust boundary. Memory tools usually optimize retrieval; this optimizes provenance, publication, redaction, sync, and review. It is closer to “agent work attached to Git history” than “agent has a long-term brain.”\\n\\nI only inspected local files and did not edit anything.\"}}","tool_name":"close_agent","tool_kind":"housekeeping","tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:32:11.505Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}